-- PRESS DIGEST - RUSSIA - Aug 8
-- 
-- Fri Aug 08, 2014 10:03AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, Aug 8 (Reuters) - The following are some of the leading stories in Russia's newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - The government is considering ways to support Russia's  state development bank VEB [VNSCB.UL], which has been hit by Western sanctions, with about 60 billion roubles every year to finance the wider economy. - Russia's Rostec, which includes state arms trader Rosoboronexport, exported arms and military equipment worth $14.2 billion last year, according to the company. - Rosneft <ROSN.MM> is asking the government to cut tax duties for equipment needed for oil extraction and allow oil producers to deal directly with their suppliers as measures to protect the oil sector from U.S. and EU sanctions.  KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev is quoted as saying that the government will direct up to 137 billion roubles to support agriculture in order to boost production of produce that will substitute for imports. - Russia has already spent 5 billion roubles to help Ukrainian refugees settle on its territory, and the figure will likely grow as the number of people seeking refuge in Russia is also growing, the daily says. - Consumers of expensive delicacies will probably suffer most of all from Russia's ban on food imports, the daily says, adding that Japanese sushi restaurants - which are especially popular with Russians - could also face serious problems. - The government approved a 681 billion rouble federal programme on the development of Crimea and its capital by 2020 on Thursday.   IZVESTIA www.izvestia.ru - Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev on Thursday signed a decree allowing free Internet access in public places only for those who present their passport. - Russian lawmakers could pass a bill toughening punishment for the use of non-government servers (gmail.com, mail.ru, yandex.ru) and cloud data storage to spread inside information, which will be treated as revealing state secrets.  ROSSIISKAYA GAZETA www.rg.ru - Police have launched criminal cases with fraud charges against the owners and senior managers of five Russian travel agencies which recently collapsed leaving thousands of Russians abroad with unpaid hotels and return plane tickets.  - Russia's ban on importing dairy products could boost prices by 10-15 percent by the end of the autumn if the government fails to take urgent measures to find new sources to replace imported milk powder, the head of the Institute of Agricultural Marketing, Yelena Tyurina, is quoted as saying.